{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656011","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656011"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:08:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18710"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.04,0,0.76,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76951"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11442"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62457"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10588"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26493"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76951"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring pregnancy, oestrogen production increases substantially above non-pregnant levels. This hormone plays crucial roles in maintaining pregnancy and preparing for childbirth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes oestrogen production during pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ovaries remain primary source throughout pregnancy","Production shifts entirely to maternal adipose tissue","Maternal adrenal gland becomes sole producer","Placenta becomes primary source after first trimester","Foetal liver assumes production after 20 weeks"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eplacenta becomes the primary source of oestrogen after the first trimester\u003C/strong\u003E of pregnancy. The placenta synthesises oestrogen using precursors from both maternal and foetal adrenal glands, producing much higher levels than the non-pregnant state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvaries remain primary source throughout pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E - While ovaries produce oestrogen early in pregnancy, the placenta takes over as the dominant source\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal adrenal gland becomes sole producer\u003C/strong\u003E - The adrenal gland provides precursors but does not directly produce oestrogen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFoetal liver assumes production after 20 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E - The foetal liver is not a significant source of oestrogen during pregnancy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction shifts entirely to maternal adipose tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - While adipose tissue can convert androgens to oestrogen, it is not a major source during pregnancy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy the third trimester, placental oestrogen production results in levels approximately 100 times higher than during the menstrual cycle. This dramatic increase supports pregnancy maintenance, foetal development, and preparation for labour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oestrogen levels rise dramatically during pregnancy due to placental production, reaching peak levels in the third trimester.","The placenta becomes the primary source of oestrogen during pregnancy, producing much higher levels than the ovaries.","Placental oestrogen synthesis requires precursors from both maternal and foetal adrenal glands."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62457"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62457"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T20:51:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T20:51:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11442"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76951"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag